How do you implement two-way data binding between components?
Companies that asked this: Salesforce, TCS, IBM, Accenture, Infosys, Capgemini

Answer:
Two-way data binding in LWC means data flows from parent to child AND changes in the child are reflected back to the parent. Since LWC doesn't have built-in two-way binding like some frameworks, we implement it using @api properties (parent→child) and custom events (child→parent).

Implementation Pattern:

Parent passes data to child via @api property

Child receives data and can modify it locally

Child dispatches event when data changes

Parent listens to event and updates its data

Updated data flows back to child via @api property

parentComponent.html

<template>
    <lightning-card title="Parent Component">
        <lightning-input label="Enter Name" value={name} onchange={handleInput}></lightning-input>
        <c-child-component name={name} onnamechange={handleNameChange}></c-child-component>
    </lightning-card>
</template>
parentComponent.js

import { LightningElement } from 'lwc';
export default class ParentComponent extends LightningElement {
    name = 'John Doe';
    handleInput(event) {
        this.name = event.target.value;
    }
    handleNameChange(event) {
        this.name = event.detail; // update parent state from child
    }
}
childComponent.html

<template>
    <lightning-input label="Child Editable Name" value={name} onchange={handleChange}></lightning-input>
</template>
childComponent.js

import { LightningElement, api } from 'lwc';
export default class ChildComponent extends LightningElement {
    @api name;
    handleChange(event) {
        const updatedName = event.target.value;
        this.dispatchEvent(new CustomEvent('namechange', { detail: updatedName }));
    }
}
